    &lt;div class=&quot;blob-title&quot;&gt;
        Adelita Grijalva was elected in Arizona three weeks ago, but Johnson refuses to swear her in &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/democrats-ramp-pressure-speaker-johnson-seat-rep-elect-adelita-grijalv-rcna237785&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;[Link&lt;span class=&quot;bi bi-link-45deg&quot;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;]&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;blob-content&quot;&gt;
        &lt;div class=&quot;image-right&quot; style=&quot;width:225px&quot;&gt;
            &lt;img class=&quot;img-link&quot; alt=&quot;Adelita Grijalva, 2024&quot; loading=&quot;lazy&quot; decoding=&quot;async&quot; style=&quot;--img-width:200&quot; src=&quot;/images/Uc9hxaaR9g-200.webp&quot; width=&quot;200&quot; height=&quot;257&quot;&gt;
            &lt;p class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Adelita Grijalva, 2024&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;It&#39;s been three weeks since Adelita Grijalva was elected to represent Arizona in the House in a special election on September 23. But House Speaker Mike Johnson refuses to swear her in, so she and her constituents have no voice in the US government.&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;Johnson has made the claim that he will not swear in Representative Grijalva until the shutdown is over, but there is no legal reason or justification for that decision: The US Congress is expected to continue to work even during a shutdown.&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;The real reason Johnson refuses to swear in Representative Grijalva is because she is expected to vote in favor of releasing the Epstein files, and her vote would push the expected total of representatives in favor of releasing the files to the 218 needed to force a vote on the issue.&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
